03751nam a22004575i 9780773555594DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735555947 a10.1515/97807735555942doi  a(DE-B1597)656119  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKE4199b.L37 2018eb 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a342.7102/92231 aLaselva, Samuel V., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCanada and the Ethics of Constitutionalism :bIdentity, Destiny, and Constitutional Faith /cSamuel V. Laselva. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tCanada and the Ethics of Constitutionalism -- tContents -- tPreface -- tThe New Canada, the Old Canada, and The Spirit of Haida Gwaii -- tThe Charter of Rights, the British Connection, and the Americanization Thesis -- tThe Notwithstanding Clause and the American Rights Model -- tBritish Judges, Charter Dialogue, and America’s “Celebrated Footnote” -- tFree Speech for the Thought That We Hate? -- tMosaic and Melting Pot -- tSecession and Identity -- tThe Spirit in the Land and the Spirit of the Constitution -- tThe Arduous Destiny of the Peaceable Kingdom -- tConstitutional Faiths -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCanada is caught between two empires and between two constitutional systems. However, neither the British model of a "single sovereign" nor the American people's "sacred fire of liberty" matched the pluralistic identity of Canada, so Canadians engaged in constitutional experimentation. In Canada and the Ethics of Constitutionalism Samuel LaSelva argues that, in order to understand the old Canada of Confederation and the new one that followed the Charter of Rights and Freedoms, it is necessary to see how distinctive Canadian constitutionalism is and how that distinctiveness does not depend on borrowings from the British or American constitutional models. LaSelva supports his argument by exploring different aspects of Canada's contribution to the ethics of constitutionalism including the limits of free expression, the Charter's notwithstanding clause, the origins and functions of judicial review, the Quebec secession debate, Aboriginal self-government, and the conception of Canada as a multicultural and multinational mosaic. Through a careful consideration of how Canadian constitutional pluralism with its focus on the rights of others differs from American and British ideas, Canada and the Ethics of Constitutionalism provides engaging answers to contested questions about how Canada was founded and what it has become.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aConstitutional historyzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355559440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773555594423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773555594/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles